               <msContents class="http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh85129656
                  http://id.loc.gov/authorities/subjects/sh85100085">
                  <summary> An excellent old copy of the <title>Mas̱navī-i maʿnavī</title> by Jalāl
                     al-Dīn Rūmī, containing all six daftars with their prefaces. </summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Uk_IO_Islamic_9-item1">
                     <author key="viaf_98930150">
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc"> Jalāl al-Dīn Rūmī </persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa">جلال الدين رومی</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_20506">Mas̱navī-i maʿnavī</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa">مثنوى معنوى</title>
                     <incipit xml:lang="fa">(f. 1v, basmala)>هذا کتاب المثنوی المعنوی و هو اصول
                        الدین فی کشف اسرار...</incipit>
                     <note>
                        <p>All the prefaces are complete in this copy. </p>
                        <p>Daftar 1: f. 1v; Daftar 2: f. 51v; Daftar 3: f. 96v; Daftar 4: f. 152v;
                           Daftar 5: f. 198v; Daftar 6: f. 250v. </p>
                        <p>Occasional readings and additions occur in the margins. </p>
                     </note>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>

               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <extent>ff. 
                           <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                              <height>359</height>
                              <width>225</width>
                           </dimensions></extent>
                        <foliation>
                           <p>Foliation in Arabic numerals on recto of each leaf. </p>
                        </foliation>
                        <condition>
                           <p>Good. Remargined throughout before 1764, the date of a former owner's
                              acquisition note. </p>
                        </condition>
                     </supportDesc>

                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="4" ruledLines="25">
                           <p>Written in four columns per page, 25 lines to the page. </p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>

                  <handDesc>
                     <summary/>
                     <handNote>
                        <p>Nastaʿlīq script in black ink with headings in red.</p>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>

                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote>Each daftar and each preface is headed by an illuminated polychrome
                        headpiece</decoNote>
                     <decoNote>The first two pages of each daftar are richly ornamented with
                        text enclosed in plain cloudbands with gold infill between lines. </decoNote>
                     <decoNote>Polychrome textframes and outer margin throughout. </decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>

                  <additions>
                     <p>Occasional marginal notes and various readings added.</p>
                     <p>Former owner's statement (f. 1r), written on top of the remargined folio,
                        records that the manuscript was purchased through one ʿIbād Allāh on 7 Rabīʿ
                        II, 1178 (4 October 1764): ...<hi rend="italic">kharīd maʻrifat ʻIbād Allāh
                           haftum Rabīʻ al-s̱ānī sanah 1178</hi>…. If this ʿIbād Allāh is the same
                        individual whose seal dated 1188 (1774/75) appears on many of Johnson’s
                        manuscripts, then the fol. 1r note must represent the declaration of an
                        intermediary owner, because Johnson did not arrive in India until 1770. The
                        1178/1764 purchase therefore predates both Johnson’s presence in India and
                        the 1188/1774–75 seal of ʿIbād Allāh. </p>
                     <p>Richard Johnson's diagonal accession statement (f. 1r): <hi rend="italic"
                           >kitāb-i sarkār Navvāb Ṣāḥib Mumtāz al-Dawlah Mufakhkhar al-Mulk Ḥusām
                           Jang Mistar Richārd Jānsan Ṣāḥib Bahādur dām iqbāluh</hi>.</p>
                  </additions>

                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1750" notAfter="1764">
                        <p>Hybrid binding, probably dating from around 1764, in red leather, gilt,
                           with a pale blue and silver floral central medallion and four vertically
                           aligned pendants; no cornerpieces. The decoration is enclosed within two
                           gilt frames ornamented with a floriate design, set inside a further
                           rectangular gilt border. </p>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                        <seal subtype="oval" type="stamp">
                        <p>Oval East India Company Library stamp (f. 1r) : ‘E.I. Company
                           Library’. </p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>

               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate calendar="#Gregorian" notBefore="1600" notAfter="11699">Undated copy
                        probably dating from the 17th century</origDate> copied most probably in
                        <origPlace>India. </origPlace>
                  </origin>

                  <provenance>
                     <p>At some point the manuscript was acquired by an individual named <persName
                           role="fmo" key="">ʿIbād Allāh</persName>, who may have been responsible
                        for its refurbishment and remargining. ʻIbād Allāh sold it to an
                        unidentified person on 7 Rabīʿ II 1178 (4 October 1764). </p>
                     <p>Subsequently it came into the possession of <persName role="fmo" key="viaf_287207857"
                           >Richard Johnson</persName>, who brought it back to England on his return
                        in 1790. </p>
                  </provenance>

                  <acquisition>
                     <p>The Johnson collection—comprising 64 albums of paintings and an estimated
                        1,000 manuscripts—was purchased by the East India Company Library for 3,000
                        guineas on <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1807-02-18">18 February
                           1807</date>. </p>
                  </acquisition>
               </history>

